@book{Saraiva2014a,
abstract = {[e aim of this thesis was to study and quantify the dynamics of bivalve communities and their innuence on the pelagic system. An individual-based population model for bivalves (using the Dynamic Energy Budget theory) was developed and coupled to a hydrodynamic and biogeochemical model (MOHID Water Modelling System). e result is a process oriented modelling tool that integrates physical, biogeochemical, ecological and physiological factors governing bivalve populated marine ecosystems. e model includes new techniques to simulate feeding processes using a mechanistic approach and a revised set of parameters is presented for the blue mussel (Mytilus edulis). e individual model was validated against observations, further extended to a population model and ultimately coupled to MOHID. A fully integrated modelling study was performed in the Balgzand ((e Netherlands). e model simulates, in a ne resolution domain, hydrodynamics (currents and water elevations), waves, heat, salt and sediment transport, biogeochemical cycle of nutrients, primary production and bivalve population dynamics. e study strengthens that there is no single mortality factor responsible for the population dynamics regulation. Early stage mortality (top-down) can control the persistence of new cohorts, in particular cannibalism and shrimp predation, although starvation (bottom-up) is the main process responsible for bivalve loss over the year in terms of biomass. e study also connrms and quantiies that bivalves do have the potential to innuence ecosystem functioning due to their role in nutrient cycling. e model is general enough to allow its application to any ecosystem with similar processes and it can simulate multiple species. Such a tool can be further used to characterize ecosystem response to diierent environmental changes (natural or anthropogenic) and to serve as an eeective and reliable management and decision making tool in estuaries and coastal areas.},
